# Public Prosecutor _v_ Dennis Teng Tai Kiat (Deng Dajie)  

### \[2022\] SGDC 186

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">District Arrest Case No 916830 of 2021, Magistrate's Appeal No 9141-2022-01</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">22 August 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Salina Bte Ishak</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Yap Poh Huat Jimmy (Traffic Police) for the Prosecution; Sunil Sudheesan and Khoo Hui-Hui Joyce (Quahe Woo &amp; Palmer LLC) acting for the accused.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Public Prosecutor — Dennis Teng Tai Kiat (Deng Dajie)</td></tr></tbody></table>

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Statutory Offences – Road Traffic Act – Drink Driving – Repeat offender

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9141/2022/01.\]

22 August 2022

### District Judge Salina Bte Ishak:

## Background

1       The accused, Mr Dennis Teng Tai Kiat (Deng Daijie), a 45-year-old male Singapore citizen faced the following charge as repeat offender for drink driving under Section 67(1)(_b_) of the Road Traffic Act, Chapter 276 (“RTA”) and punishable under Section 67(1) read with Section 67(2)(_b_) of the said Act:

> are charged that you, on the 08 June 2021, at about 2.41 a.m., at the open space carpark of Bishan Street 13 near to Block 157, Singapore, whilst driving motorcar, SMZ7525R, did have so much alcohol in your body that the proportion of it in your blood, to wit, not less than 201 milligrams of alcohol in every 100 milliliters of blood, exceeded the prescribed limit of 80 milligrams of alcohol in 100 millilitres of blood and you have thereby committed an offence under Section 67(1)(b) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”). And further, that you, before the commission of the said offence, had been convicted on 30 April 2009, at the Subordinate Court of Singapore, for an offence of Drink Driving under Section 67(1)(b) of the Road Traffic Act, Chapter 276 (DAC/16388/09), which conviction has not been set aside, and you are now liable for punishment under Section 67(1) read with Section 67(2) (b) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”).

2       On 14 July 2022, he pleaded guilty to the charge and admitted to the Statement of Facts without any qualification.

3       After carefully considering the Prosecution’s submissions on sentence as well as the Defence’s written plea in mitigation, I sentenced the accused to six weeks’ imprisonment, a fine of $9,000 and disqualified him from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of six years with effect from release. I ordered the sentence to take effect from 28 July 2022 after the Defence sought a deferment of the sentence. He had paid the fine in full on 14 July 2022.

4       The accused being dissatisfied with my decision had filed a Notice of Appeal against his sentence on 27 July 2022. A stay of execution has been granted for his imprisonment term. He is currently on bail pending his appeal.

5       Having set out the background for the present case, I now provide the reasons for my decision.

## Salient Facts

6       The complainant is one Sergeant Mohammed Fizzi attached to Traffic Police. The accused was the driver of motorcar SMZ7525R.

7       On 7 June 2021 at about 7.30pm, the accused was at his friend’s place located in the vicinity of Cairnhill where he had consumed slightly more than a bottle of red wine between 8.30pm till 12am on 8 June 2021. The accused left his friend’s place at about 1 plus am and he was driven home by a valet driver. On arriving at the open space carpark of Bishan Street 13, the valet driver had parked the accused’s car at lot number 30 which was in-front of Block 154 Bishan Street 13 and the valet driver left the location leaving the accused alone in his car.

8       On the same day at about 2.41am, the police received a phone call from a member of public who saw the accused’s car along the carpark’s driveway in-front of Block 157 Bishan Street 13. The car was believed to have mounted the road kerb and the accused was seen to be opening and closing his door. Shortly after, the accused was seen reversing his car and he drove off in the direction of Block 158 Bishan Street 13.

![](data:image;base64,)

![](data:image;base64,)

9       The complainant and his partner were despatched to the incident and on their arrival, they spotted the accused’s motorcar parked at lot number 270 which was in-front of Block 158 Bishan Street 13. The complainant noticed the accused was at the driver’s seat of his motorcar and the driver’s door was ajar. Upon interviewing, the complainant observed the accused reeked of alcohol and he admitted consuming alcohol prior to arriving at the current location. The complainant proceeded to administer a breathalyser test on the accused and the result shown was ‘Fail’. The accused was arrested for driving under the influence of alcohol and he was escorted to Traffic Police for Breath Analysing Device (BAD) test.

10     On arrival in Traffic Police, the accused was examined by a duty nurse and he was found to be unfit for detention in view of his low blood sugar and complains of pain to his legs. The accused was then escorted to Changi General Hospital (CGH) for medical attention and blood test to be conducted. In CGH, the accused gave his consent to the doctor for his blood to be drawn for the purpose of alcohol analysis.

11     An analyst, Nadia Norashikin Bti A S Wong, from Analytical Toxicology Laboratory of the Health Sciences Authority, analysed the blood sample of the accused and issued a report dated 17 June 2021. The report revealed that the proportion of alcohol in accused’s blood contained 201 milligrams of alcohol in every 100 millilitres of blood. The prescribed limit is 80 milligrams of alcohol per 100 millilitres of blood.

12     As the accused had been previously convicted at the Subordinate Court of Singapore on the 30 April 2009, for an offence of drink driving under s 67(1)(b) of the RTA which conviction has not been set aside, and he shall be punished as a repeat offender under s 67(1) read with s 67(2)(b) of the RTA.

## Sentencing

### Prescribed Penalty

13     The prescribed penalty for a second or subsequent offence of drink driving under s 67(1)(_b_) of the RTA is a fine of not less than $5,000 and not more than $20,000 and to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 2 years. In addition, pursuant to s 67(2)(_b_) of the RTA unless the court for special reasons thinks fit to not order or to order otherwise, the court must order that the person be disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for at least five years for a repeat offender.

## Antecedents

14     On 30 April 2009, the accused was convicted in Court 21 for an offence of drink driving under s 67(1)(_b_) of the RTA and was fined $2,000 and disqualified for 12 months.

## Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

15     The Prosecution had submitted that the accused was a repeat offender for the offence of drink driving. Although his antecedent was 13 years ago for the present charge, his alcohol level at 87.9µg after conversion from his blood alcohol level, fell within Band 3 of _Rafael Voltaire Alzate v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGHC 224</span> (“_Rafael Voltaire_”). In view of the high alcohol level, the Prosecution sought an imprisonment term of between eight to ten weeks, a fine of between $10,000 to $15,000 and a disqualification for a period of seven years.

## Mitigation

16     In his written plea in mitigation, his Defence Counsel Mr. Sunil Sudheesan had set out the circumstances of the present case, his client’s medical condition as well as the sentencing considerations. He had urged the Court to impose two to three weeks’ imprisonment, a high fine and a 6-year disqualification from driving all classes of vehicles.

#### Circumstances of the present case

17     According to the Defence on 7 June 2021 at or around 7.30pm, the accused had wine while having dinner at his friend’s place. He left his friend’s place at around 1.00am on 8 June 2021 and was driven home by a valet driver (“driver”). When they arrived at the carpark near the accused’s home at 1.35am, the driver had parked the car 100 metres away from his block. The accused told the valet to park closer to our client’s block but there were no vacant lots near his block at that time. The accused remained in his car after the driver left.

18     Sometime after 2.00am, the accused woke up and realised that his car was parked some distance away from his block. He drove towards Block 155 of Bishan Street 13 and spotted a vacant parking lot less than 50m away from his block. While moving the car, he mounted the road kerb. Following this, he reversed from the road kerb and proceeded to park his car. It was highlighted that the car did not suffer any damage and did not require any repair work. No accident or injury was caused to anyone as a result his actions.

19     It was submitted that the incident took place at around 2.41am in an open space carpark where traffic flow at that time was virtually non-existent. The accused had not driven his car outside of the carpark and the total distance covered was only around 80 to 100m.

#### The accused’s medical condition

20     It was the Defence’s position that he needed his car to be parked nearer to his block as he is not able to walk long distances due to Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 1A (“CMT1A”), a hereditary neurological disorder that affects the peripheral nerves. He experiences weakness and sensory loss due to his condition. When he was arrested, he was experiencing leg pains to the extent that he could not stand up without falling over.

21     In support of his medical condition, the Defence had tendered the following documents:

> (a)     A memorandum dated 27 December 2021 by Dr Chong Piang Ngok (“Dr Chong”) of P N Chong Neurology Clinic;

> (b)     A medical report dated 31 May 2022 by Dr Josiah Chai Yui Huei (“Dr Josiah”) of the National Neuroscience Institute (“NNI”) at Tan Tock Seng Hospital and

> (c)     A memorandum dated 17 June 2022 by Dr Josiah who observed that there is no specific treatment for the accused’s condition. He requires physiotherapy to help him maintain his strength. He was also advised to get an ankle foot orthosis for our client’s foot drop.

#### Sentencing considerations

22     It was submitted that the accused’s blood alcohol level was 201mg per 100ml of blood, which translates to a BEA reading of around 88µg. The Defence referred to the sentencing framework set out by Menon CJ in _Rafael Voltaire Alzate v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] 3 SLR 993</span> (“_Rafael Voltaire_”) (at \[31\]) with respect to first-time drink drivers.

23     It was further submitted that applying the _Rafael Voltaire_ framework, the appropriate range of fines would be $6,000 to $8,000 and the appropriate disqualification sentence would fall between 36 and 48 months. As the accused is a second-time offender, the Defence recognised that an appropriate and fair upward adjustment to the eventual sentence must be made.

24     The Defence had referred to Menon’s CJ decision in _Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> (“_Edwin Suse_”) which sets out the factors which may aggravate or mitigate the gravity of an offence under s 67(1)(_b_) of the RTA. These factors include the driver’s manner of driving, the circumstances of driving, and reasons for driving at \[27\] and \[28\].

25     In the present case, it was submitted that the accused only drove for a very short distance of around 80 to 100m. He drove in a very slow manner in an open carpark at all material times and the flow of traffic was negligible. It was further submitted that the only reason he drove his car that night was because of his hereditary medical condition, which resulted in his limited ability to walk. According to the Defence, the accused is a person who with a drop of alcohol will always call the valet. As a result of his work, he needs to go entertaining relatively frequently and on a weekly basis would call a valet about two to three times a week. He had made a very silly error of driving to go and find a carpark lot that was closer to his home.

26     It was the Defence’s position that while it recognised that this was his second drink-driving offence, the circumstances leading to him driving at the material time are not that of a typical drink driving case. His driving did not lead to any injury or any property damage at all. Applying the _Rafael Voltaire_ framework and the aggravating and mitigating factors highlighted above, it was submitted that the accused’s level of culpability should be pegged at the low end of the medium range while the level of harm was very low. It was further submitted that as the present case is a unique case, there was more than enough scope to consider significantly reducing the sentence as proposed by the Prosecution.

27     In support of its sentencing position of two to three weeks’ imprisonment, a high fine and a 6-year disqualification from driving all classes of vehicles, the Defence had relied on _Public Prosecutor v Vijayan Mahadevan_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGDC 52</span> (“_Vijayan Mahadevan_”) and _Public Prosecutor v Lian Chee Wee_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] SGDC 103</span> (“_Lian Chee Wee_”).

## Prosecution’s Reply

28     In response to the Defence’s reliance on _Vijayan Mahadevan_, it was submitted that this was case on appeal and the outcome was still pending. It was further submitted that the accused’s level of alcohol was very high which indicates his unfitness to drive. The fact remained that the accused did drink and drive.

29     The Prosecution referred to a footage which captured the accused’s vehicle being mounted on a kerb. According to the Prosecution, the footage showed that the accused had been sitting in the vehicle for quite some time and he had managed to reverse slowly before driving off.

## Decision on sentence

30     In the present case, I was mindful that as a repeat offender for drink driving, the accused was liable to a mandatory imprisonment for a term not exceeding 2 years, a fine of not less than $5,000 and not more than $20,000 and mandatory disqualification of at least 5 years. As at the date of my decision, there is no existing sentencing framework enunciated by the High Court for repeat offenders for drink driving under s 67(2)(_b_) of the RTA.

31     The increase in penalties for drivers who are drunk or drug-impaired arose out of a review of the RTA and it aimed to provide stiffer punishment to signal the aggravated seriousness of their actions. This is according to the explanation presented by the Second Minister for Home Affairs, Mrs Josephine Teo (the “Minister”) to Parliament on 8 July 2019 (_Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report_ (8 July 2019), vol 94). The Minister’s explanation is set out below:

> …Drivers who are drunk or drug impaired show a blatant disregard for the safety of other road users. They are one of the biggest contributors to serious accidents on our roads. These are also accidents that clearly could have been avoided if the motorist had not come under the influence or did not drive. Currently, such motorists typically face the same maximum penalties as other motorists who cause accidents. The judge may take into consideration that the offender was driving under influence during the sentencing itself. But it would be clearer to have our intentions codified in law. In fact, our intention is for offenders driving under influence to face stiffer penalties to signal the aggravated seriousness of their actions…

> Mr Speaker, during the public engagement process, respondents felt that even standalone driving under influence offence where no accident is caused, should attract higher penalties to better attract its gravity.

> We agree with this view. The consumption of alcohol or drugs already makes a motorist a danger to other road users. Section 67 in Clause 17 of the Bill will raise the penalties to double the current levels. We will also raise the existing minimum DQ period to two years for first-time driving under influence offenders and five years for second-time driving under influence offenders. A lifelong disqualification will be imposed for third-time driving under influence offenders. In addition, we will amend section 47C through Clause 11 to allow Traffic Police to impose immediate suspension for all driving while under influence offenders.

32     Based on the sentencing framework in _Rafael Voltaire_ as a neutral starting point for first time drink drivers, the accused’s alcohol level at about 88_µg_ would have placed him within almost at the highest end of Band 3 _ie_ between 70 to 89_µg_ where the range of fines is between $6,000 to $8,000 and disqualification of between 36 to 48 months. Based on his level of alcohol alone, the accused’s culpability would have been within the moderate range as it fell within the second highest band of the sentencing framework.

33     When sentencing, I would still have to calibrate the sentence upwards to factor in the mandatory imprisonment term as the accused is a repeat offender and consider whether there was any aggravating or mitigating circumstances. In determining the appropriate sentence, I would also consider other relevant factors such as the manner of driving, his reasons for driving, the type of vehicle, the distance travelled, the road and traffic conditions, any impairment of the ability to drive or whether there was accident resulting in harm to person or property and the duration between the last offence and his present charge.

34     The Defence had relied on _Vijayan Mahadevan_ and _Lian Chee Wee_ to seek a sentence of two to three weeks’ imprisonment, a high fine and a 6-year disqualification from driving all classes of vehicles. I noted in _Vijayan Mahadevan_, the offender’s alcohol level was similarly within Band 3 at 76_µg_, he was stopped at a roadblock and had claimed trial. The accused in that case had appealed against his conviction and the sentence of eight weeks’ imprisonment, a fine of $10,000 and the 7 years disqualification. As at the time of my decision, his appeal has not been heard by the High Court.

35     In _Lian Chee Wee_, the offender’s alcohol level was 69 _µg_, he was stopped at a roadblock and had pleaded guilty. I was of the view that this case was not useful as a precedent as it was decided prior to the Road Traffic (Amendment) Act 2019 (Act 19 of 2019) on 1 November 2019. The prescribed penalty for repeat offender was then a fine of not less than $3,000 and not more than $10,000 and to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months. The offender in that case was sentenced to two weeks’ imprisonment, a fine of $4,500 and disqualification of 42 months. As set out above, the maximum fine as well as the imprisonment term has since been doubled and there is a mandatory disqualification period of 5 years for repeat offenders.

36     In the present case, I considered the fact that unlike a typical roadblock situation, the police were activated by a concerned member of public who at about 2.41am had observed the accused opening and closing his door after he had mounted the kerb along the carpark’s driveway in-front of Block 157 Bishan Street 13. From the footage tendered by the Prosecution, the accused was in his vehicle for at least 5 minutes before he was seen reversing his car and driving off in the direction of Block 158 Bishan Street 13.

37     I observed that from the footage provided by a member of the public, the accused’s vehicle was against the kerb along the driveway in an awkward position. When the police arrived, the accused’s motorcar was parked at lot number 270 which was in front of Block 158 Bishan Street 13. The accused was at the driver’s seat of his motorcar and the driver’s door was ajar.

38     In my view, the accused clearly show a blatant disregard for the safety of other road users as well as the prohibition against driving while under the influence of drinks when he chose to move his car to another parking lot for his own convenience. The accused would not have mounted the kerb had he not driven when he was clearly too inebriated to do so. He was clearly aware that he was in no condition to drive as he had engaged the services of a valet to drive him home. The accused’s inexplicable act of opening and closing his door after he had mounted the kerb along the carpark’s driveway and in the process causing unnecessary obstruction had caused enough concern for the member of public to seek police assistance. It is evident that the impairment of the accused’s ability to drive was due to the high levels of alcohol found in his body.

39     The Defence has sought to characterise the present case as a unique case as the accused had driven his car that night due to a hereditary medical condition, which resulted in his limited ability to walk. From the medical evidence produced by the Defence it was clear that while the accused had difficulty walking long distances, there was no evidence that he was unable to walk the 100m to his block. There was also no evidence that he was unable to return home unaided even when his car was parked 50m from his home. Instead, the Defence had conceded that he made a very silly error of driving to find a carpark that was closer to his home.

40     In my view, as the accused was subsequently found by the police in the driver’s seat with the door open even after moving his car closer to his home, this showed that he was just too inebriated to make his way home. There was clearly no extenuating circumstances or emergency which necessitates his decision to drive that would have reduced his culpability. Based on the above facts, I was of the view that the accused’s culpability was moderate and the level of harm was low as there was no injury or property damage.

#### Sentence

41     In the present case, after considering the offence-specific factors such as his level of alcohol which was at the second highest band of _Rafael Voltaire_, his manner of driving including the fact that he had mounted a kerb and the relatively short distance he drove within the carpark during the early hours of the morning, I was of the view that the starting point for the present charge is eight weeks’ imprisonment and a fine of at least $10,000. As the accused had pleaded guilty to the charge and he had reoffended 12 years after his driving ban ended, I had calibrated the sentence downwards to six weeks’ imprisonment and a fine of $9,000 to fulfil the objectives of punishment, the protection of the public and deterrence. The fine of $9,000 represents an uplift from the maximum Band 3 fine of $8000 for a first offender under the _Rafael Voltaire_ framework.

42     In my view, the sentence of two to three weeks’ imprisonment and a high fine proposed by the Defence was manifestly inadequate in view of the accused’s moderate culpability as well as the aggravated seriousness of the accused’s actions. Although the Prosecution had sought a similar sentence as that in _Vijayan Mahadevan_, I was mindful that the offender there had claimed trial to the charge and the appeal against his conviction and sentence is pending. In addition, in that case the offender had driven to a pharmacy that was 150m from his house and then drove to a petrol kiosk that was about 300 to 400m away from the pharmacy. In the present case the accused had driven for about 80 to 100m within the carpark. Hence, a downward calibration of the proposed sentence was necessary in the present case.

#### Disqualification Order

43     In the present case, pursuant to s 67(2)(_b_) of the RTA unless the court for special reasons thinks fit to not order or to order otherwise, the court must order that the person be disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for at least five years for a repeat offender.

44     In deciding on the appropriate period of disqualification, I was mindful that the disqualification order and the sentence imposed are not mutually compensatory; an increase in the quantum of the fine imposed should not be taken to mandate the imposition of a reduced period of disqualification than would otherwise have been ordered: _Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> at \[13\].

45     In determining the appropriate length of the disqualification order, I was guided by the approach in the recent case of _Kwan Weiguang v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 121</span> (“_Kwan_”). Although Aedit Abdullah J dealt with an appeal against a disqualification order of 15 months that was imposed on the appellant for an offence of dangerous driving under s 64(1) and punishable under s 64(2C)(_a_) of the RTA, the factors considered are relevant to the present case. He held at \[59\] and \[61\] that the objective of the disqualification order is as follow:

> A driving disqualification order combines three sentencing objectives: punishment, protection of the public and deterrence (_Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> (“_Edwin Nathen_”) at \[13\]). Often, due to the limited range of fines in the punishment provision, the impact of a disqualification order is likely to be felt much more acutely than any marginal increase in the quantum of the fine (see Edwin Nathen at \[13\])…

> 61 A disqualification order also serves to remove the privilege to drive from those who have abused it, and this also reinforces the notion of shared usage of the roads. It must be remembered that driving is an inherently dangerous activity. The licence to drive is a privilege accorded to persons who, through a series of properly administered tests, have demonstrated that they are capable of meeting the standards expected of a reasonably competent driver (_Jali bin Mohd Yunos v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 4 SLR 1059</span> at \[36\]). The former Minister for Home Affairs, Prof S Jayakumar, had expressed the following view which reinforces this notion (see Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report (28 March 1990) vol 55 at col 960): “… we must get every driver in Singapore to note that when he is issued a licence, it is in fact a very special privilege and it is granted on condition that he drives in a responsible manner bearing in mind the interest of others.”

46     In _Kwan_ at \[65\] to \[71\], the relevant and material factors when determining the period of disqualification are:

> (a)     Circumstances of the commission of the offence;

> (b)     Continued ability to drive and attitude towards other road users.

47     In the present case, no special reasons relating to the offence was provided by the Defence for the court not to impose the mandatory disqualification order. Instead, the Defence had sought a disqualification for 6 years. It was also clear that it was within the public’s interest to remove such a driver from the roads for a substantial period of time.

48     In my view, after taking the circumstances of the commission of the offence into account, I agreed with the Defence that a disqualification period of 6 years for all classes of vehicles was appropriate to fulfil the objectives of punishment, the protection of the public and deterrence. An uplift from the prescribed minimum period of 5 years was necessary in view of the twin factors of harm and culpability in the present case. A disqualification period of 7 years sought by the Prosecution would have been excessive in view of the accused’s plea of guilt and the circumstances of the present case as an uplift of 2 years from the prescribed minimum disqualification period was not warranted.

## Conclusion

49     All things considered, I was of the view that the sentence of six weeks’ imprisonment, a fine of $9,000 in default 30 days’ imprisonment and a disqualification from a period of 6 years from release was just and appropriate in the circumstances.
